Taylor,

We have hundreds of thousands of merchants. The customers at issue here are all extremely large, sophisticated, multi-location merchants most of whom are getting rates from us in the low single digits and process millions of dollars a month - some close to a billion a year. You are correct that we should have included language addressing active solicitations of customers from this population (ex. proactive price decreases within 6-months of an RTO program event to retain a customer, etc.). While this language was missed, it is almost insulting that Card Connect would exploit this detail when my brother and 1 did a good deed that resulted in Card Connect retaining tens of millions of dollars in processing volume and the $500k or so per month of revenue it generates. This is completely wrong. It is also inconsistent with the spirit of our agreement and the environment of complete trust required between our organizations.

As the email below indicates, Card Connect would never be in this position to begin with if we didn't approve the RTO program for Card Connect. The email also indicates that Card Connect knew we would pursue reasonable actions to retain the merchants. In fact, Card Connect was hoping that "Shift4 stepping in keeps many others on platform." This is what we did. Per the email below, everyone here is on the same page regarding the interpretation of the agreement; and it specifically contemplates Shift4 taking action to retain merchants.

The volume at issue at Card Connect is less than 1 basis point of your total. Our good will of waiving our RTO, saved an amount of volume worth 40 basis points of your processing revenue. The agreement already contains language protecting our business interests. If the terms of our agreement, after our good will is considered, are still not acceptable to Card Connect you are more than welcome to refund everything we saved you and we can resume our RTO program. Jered,

I wanted to follow up on this matter one more time, particularly in light of the call you and I had earlier today regarding our respective organizations working more closely together. I understand that the agreement, that my team put in place over a year ago, does not prevent Shift4 from taking actions necessary to protect its legitimate business interests when faced with a merchant exercising or threatening to exercise a right to terminate provision. I do not believe it is appropriate, however, for Shift4 to actively solicit, induce, or encourage customers to do so. It certainly undermines the partnership and spirit of our agreement.

As partners, we need to maintain and have a mutual understanding and respect of each other's position. Can we agree that the agreement prohibits the active, outward solicitation, inducement, or encouragement of merchants to exercise their right to terminate, and that we can continue to partner in a way that recognizes these boundaries?

Taylor,

The intent of the email was simply to get a meeting together and
communicate that this situation is going to get a lot worse before it
gets better – which is not good for Card Connect, Shift4 or First Data.
We had a call scheduled for tomorrow to discuss various topics as well
as a number of Shift4 opportunities that we are driving to Card Connect,
but I do not see any value in that meeting now.

While you were correct in your last email that it doesn’t matter what I
think the agreement says, since its Card Connect and Shift4 who are the
contracting parties, you failed to recognize that I have a valuable
perspective considering I was one of the two people to negotiate the
agreement on behalf of Shift4. Now, as I have communicated to you and
Randy numerous times, I will share that perspective in order of importance.

   1. First, the agreement contains many areas open to interpretation.
      I can assure you that the perspective I have communicated to
      you already is consistent with Shift4’s position. The agreement
      will likely say whatever First Data and Shift4 collectively agree
      it says. I will also reiterate my belief that this focus is very
      misguided and petty, but if you want to spend money changing that
      – there is nothing preventing you from doing so.
   2. Next, the history. There have been hundreds of customers on the
      RTO list that were flagged in error, such as Kona Grill, and our
      team simply excluded them which eliminated considerable and
      unnecessary distractions. The same is true on the revenue share
      reporting side. There have been over 100 merchants that should
      have been flagged as revenue share merchants, yet weren’t, and we
      excluded them from the program. This was all done for the
      benefit of Card Connect, the spirit of the partnership as
      evidenced by the email below in which Card Connect says “as
      we all know there are many merchants that threaten to RTO a
      contract and do not” and “Shift4 stepping in keeps many others.”
      We are not going to change that approach.

   3. I will say again, and I know you do not care, but I am not sure
      why you are spending so much of your very valuable time on $25k in
      monthly revenue which is not even 1 basis point of your total
      volume when you are essentially sitting on a ticking time bomb in
      terms of merchant attrition as a result of all the chaos at First
      Data. I know some of your largest customers are getting quotes
      from competitors (I receive calls from them all the time) so I
      just think this is such a huge distraction.

In terms of having a productive dialogue, I am certainly open to it
although you are the one that communicated you only wanted to have such
communications through counsel which is why I said I would comply with
your request. My offer still stands from my email below that you can
refund us all the volume we saved Card Connect, and we can put the
merchants back on the program. Please advise how you would like to
proceed.

Jered
